Reference-contexts: Usefulness of math and perceived value of math accounts for a portion of the gender differences in some studies, along with gender-stereotyped parental beliefs and math anxiety <ref> (Jacklin 1989) </ref>. Researchers in education have increasingly called for the use of longitudinal and hierarchical designs in order to examine the process of education.
Reference: <author> Kimball, M.M. </author> <year> 1989. </year> <title> "A New Perspective on Women's Math Achievement". </title> <journal> Psychological Bulletin 105: </journal> <pages> 198-214. </pages>
Reference-contexts: One factor that may contribute to the gender-related differences is exposure to math; males enroll in more math courses than females, and it has been posited that they have more exposure to mathematics outside of the classroom <ref> (Kimball 1989) </ref>. Controlling for the number of advanced math courses does diminish the differences between males and females on standardized math achievement tests, but it does not completely eliminate them. Gender-related differences in math exposure outside of the classroom may contribute to gender differences as well. <p> In addition, some research has found that academic and non-academic interactions in the classroom occur more frequently for males, and males receive more encouragement, praise and discipline while females receive more discouragement <ref> (Kimball 1989) </ref>. High achievers received more attention than low achievers in one study, and high-achieving males and low-achieving females received more attention than high-achieving females in another study. One study found that females receive better grades in a cooperative atmosphere as opposed to a competitive one. <p> Gender-related learning styles may be partially responsible for the sex differences favoring females in the classroom and the differences favoring males on achievement tests <ref> (Kimball 1989) </ref>. Specifically, some evidence suggests that females have a rote memorization learning style while that of males may be characterized as autonomous.
