Reference-contexts: Introduction Until around the middle of the twentieth century, gender differences in intellectual abilities were considered "natural" or inherently dependent on biological sex differences <ref> (Sadker, Sadker, and Klein 1991) </ref>. The landmark publication of Maccoby and Jacklin's The Psychology of Sex Differences in 1974 raised many questions concerning the biological basis of gender differences. <p> In subsequent research, both biological and environmental variables have been posited as "causes" of these gender-related differences. Biological explanations focus on the relationship between exposure to testosterone in utero and hemispheric activity in the brain, while environmental explanations are centered on childhood socialization and child-rearing practices <ref> (Sadker, et al 1991) </ref>. One problem that is not addressed in this research is the inability to isolate the effects of gender socialization from observed biological sex when observational data is used. Past research has discovered many intermediate variables, or covariates that are indicators of gender/math socialization.
